Post nmqnitudinem mrminis Romani, lit, “Since the greatness of the Roman name,” i. e., “After the Roman name had become great.” 5. Rex Numidarum. Numidia was a country of Africa east of Mauritania, and corresponding nearly to modern Algiers. It was originally divided into two petty kingdoms, that of the Massyli to the east, of which Masinissa was king, and that of the Massaesyli to the west, governed by Syphax, who, having taken part with the Cartha· ginians, was conquered by Laelius and Masinissa, and his territory, after the close of the second Punic war, bestowed by the Romans on Masinissa during his life, who thus became king of all Numidia. As a people, the Numidicus are represented by Sallust as wal-like, but faithless, nnsteady, and fond of revolutions in the state. 6.
